1. Choose a Server Provider
Get a remote server (e.g., AWS, DigitalOcean, or any VPS provider) with a public IP.
2. Install a Proxy Server
On your remote server, you can install a proxy server like 3proxy or Squid.

Example for 3proxy:
SSH into your remote server:

bash
Copy code
ssh username@your_server_ip
Update the package manager and install the necessary dependencies:

bash
Copy code
sudo apt update
sudo apt install build-essential wget
Download and compile 3proxy:

bash
Copy code
wget https://github.com/z3APA3A/3proxy/archive/refs/tags/0.9.4.tar.gz
tar -xvzf 0.9.4.tar.gz
cd 3proxy-0.9.4
make -f Makefile.Linux
Configure the proxy by editing the 3proxy.cfg file:

bash
Copy code
sudo nano /etc/3proxy/3proxy.cfg
Example configuration:

bash
Copy code
nserver 8.8.8.8
nserver 8.8.4.4
nscache 65536
timeout 120
users user:CL:password
allow user
proxy -p3128
Replace user and password with your desired credentials.
The -p3128 part is the port where the proxy will be accessible.
Start 3proxy:

bash
Copy code
sudo ./3proxy /etc/3proxy/3proxy.cfg
Set it to run on startup:

bash
Copy code
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/3proxy.service
Add the following content:

ini
Copy code
[Unit]
Description=3proxy
After=network.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/3proxy /etc/3proxy/3proxy.cfg
Restart=on-failure

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
Enable the service:

bash
Copy code
sudo systemctl enable 3proxy
sudo systemctl start 3proxy
3. Configure Telegram
Open Telegram on your device.
Go to Settings > Data and Storage > Proxy Settings.
Add your proxy server:
Type: HTTP
Server: Your server’s IP
Port: The port you configured (e.g., 3128)
Username/Password: (if required by your configuration)
Once configured, your Telegram traffic will route through the proxy server.
